# radix-ui Best Practices

Radix UI is a powerful library for building accessible, headless UI components in React. This guide outlines essential practices to ensure your components are robust, maintainable, and performant.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use the `asChild` Prop
When integrating Radix components with your own or existing DOM elements, always use the `asChild` prop. This allows for proper forwarding of refs, event handlers, and ARIA attributes without unnecessary wrappers.

❌ BAD
```jsx
<Dialog>
  <button>Open Dialog</button>
</Dialog>
```

✅ GOOD
```jsx
<Dialog>
  <button asChild>Open Dialog</button>
</Dialog>
```

### Build Product-Specific Abstractions
Avoid importing raw Radix primitives globally. Instead, create abstractions tailored to your product's needs. This approach minimizes the risk of breaking changes when updating dependencies.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
// Button.js
import { Button as RadixButton } from '@radix-ui/react-button';

const Button = ({ children, ...props }) => {
  return <RadixButton {...props}>{children}</RadixButton>;
};
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Controlled vs. Uncontrolled State
Choose either controlled or uncontrolled state patterns, but never mix them. Use `defaultOpen` or `defaultValue` for internal management, and `open` and `onOpenChange` when your app manages the state.

❌ BAD
```jsx
<Accordion defaultOpen={true} open={isOpen} onOpenChange={setIsOpen}>
  ...
</Accordion>
```

✅ GOOD
```jsx
<Accordion open={isOpen} onOpenChange={setIsOpen}>
  ...
</Accordion>
```

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize Rendering with Memoization
Use `React.memo` to prevent unnecessary re-renders of components that do not change frequently. This is particularly useful for complex Radix components.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
const MemoizedComponent = React.memo(({ data }) => {
  return <SomeRadixComponent data={data} />;
});
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Inline Styles
Avoid using inline styles for Radix components as they can lead to performance issues and make styling harder to manage.

❌ BAD
```jsx
<Dialog style={{ backgroundColor: 'white' }}>
  ...
</Dialog>
```

✅ GOOD
```jsx
<Dialog className="bg-white">
  ...
</Dialog>
```

## Component Architecture

### Keep Layout Logic Outside Components
Maintain a clear separation of layout logic from component logic. This ensures components remain focused on behavior and presentation.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
const Layout = () => {
  return (
    <div className="flex">
      <Sidebar />
      <MainContent />
    </div>
  );
};
```

## State Management

### Use Context for Global State
For managing global state across Radix components, leverage React's Context API. This avoids prop drilling and keeps your components clean.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
const GlobalStateContext = React.createContext();

const App = () => {
  const [state, setState] = useState(initialState);

  return (
    <GlobalStateContext.Provider value={{ state, setState }}>
      <YourComponent />
    </GlobalStateContext.Provider>
  );
};
```

## Accessibility

### Ensure ARIA Attributes are Present
Always ensure that ARIA attributes are correctly set on Radix components to maintain accessibility standards. This is crucial for users relying on assistive technologies.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
<Dialog aria-labelledby="dialog-title" aria-describedby="dialog-description">
  <h2 id="dialog-title">Dialog Title</h2>
  <p id="dialog-description">Description of the dialog</p>
</Dialog>
```

## Hooks Best Practices

### Use Custom Hooks for Reusable Logic
Encapsulate reusable logic in custom hooks to keep components clean and focused. This is especially useful for managing state or side effects related to Radix components.

✅ GOOD
```jsx
const useDialogState = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);
  const toggle = () => setIsOpen((prev) => !prev);
  return { isOpen, toggle };
};

// Usage
const MyComponent = () => {
  const { isOpen, toggle } = useDialogState();
  return <Dialog open={isOpen} onOpenChange={toggle}>...</Dialog>;
};
```

By following these best practices, you will ensure that your use of Radix UI is effective, maintainable, and accessible, leading to a better experience for both developers and users.